article.description:
David West's career-high 47 points and 18
rebounds helped 20th-ranked Xavier rally from a 15-point deficit to
beat Dayton 85-77 Saturday.
article.headline: West, Xavier snap Dayton's nine-game win streak

images.name: West_David 020803 inline
images.caption: David West scored 18 of Xavier's first 20 points Saturday.

article.linkText: West pours in 47 points in Xavier's win over Dayton
article.story: CINCINNATI (AP) --Finally given the freedom to show his stuff, David West made jaws drop: 47 points, 18 rebounds, nearly a double-double in each half. And it wasn't against some overmatched high school team. West put on his show against the last unbeaten team in Atlantic 10 play, with a pair of 6-foot-11 defenders draped on him. West had the second-best scoring game in school history Saturday, swishing shots from every spot on the floor as No. 20 Xavier rallied for an 85-77 victory over Dayton. The preseason All-America led Xavier (17-4, 8-1) out of a 15-point deficit in the first half, when he had 22 points and eight rebounds -- two rebounds shy of a double-double in the half alone. He was only warming up. The 6-foot-9 forward took advantage of Dayton's man-to-man coverage by hitting 15-of-26 from the field, including his only 3-point shot. He also sank 16-of-19 from the line and dominated on the boards. "There was a guy today that saved us -- David West,'' Xavier coach Thad Matta said. "That was one of the best college performances I've ever seen. He was spectacular, just all around.'' Steve Thomas set the Xavier record of 50 points on Jan. 6, 1964, against Detroit. Dayton (16-4, 8-1) didn't have a clue how to stop him, sealing yet another loss in Cincinnati. The Flyers had a nine-game winning streak snapped as they lost their 18th in a row on Xavier's home court. "I thought if we got it to the last six minutes and it was a game, we had a chance with our experience and poise,'' Dayton coach Oliver Purnell said. "We almost had to play perfectly because we couldn't stop West down the stretch.'' They couldn't stop him at any point. West scored Xavier's first 13 points and 18 of its first 20, shooting over or muscling through Dayton's two 6-foot-11 post players -- Sean Finn and Keith Waleskowski. West stuck around for his senior season rather than go into the NBA, expecting big things out of himself and the Musketeers. Injuries have held Xavier back, and West has been swarmed by double- and triple-teaming defenses nearly every game. Purnell decided to try something different. He had the Flyers guard West in a straight-up, man-to-man defense. "That was the first time since my freshman year that I didn't get double-teamed,'' West said. "I was waiting for it, but it never came, so coach kept calling my number. That's probably the last time I'll see it this year.'' Dayton eventually tried double-teaming West with both of its big men, went to a soft zone, even tried to press to get West out of his game. Nothing worked for long. "When the guy gets going, you just give him the ball,'' point guard Lionel Chalmers said. "We just had to be patient, get the ball to David West and let him score 50.'' The 47 points were three shy of Xavier's record, and second all-time in the Atlantic 10. Xavier broadcaster Byron Larkin, who scored 45 for the Musketeers in 1986, sat courtside and marveled. Larkin considered it much more impressive than LeBron James putting up big numbers against a high school defense. James is expected to be the first pick in the NBA draft, with West not far behind. "In a college game of this magnitude, it's something special,'' Larkin said. "There's an intensity here that you just don't have at the high school level. That's what makes this more impressive.'' The Flyers came out running fastbreaks and surged ahead by 15. West set up a frenetic second half -- three ties, 13 lead changes. West's two free throws with 3:52 left started a 10-point spurt that put Xavier in control. Waleskowski matched his career high with 24 points, but gave up most of West's baskets. "I feel like I played awful, and I'm pretty upset about that,'' he said. "That was the worst defensive game of my life.'' West has played with a severely bruised right hand since he hurt it in practice Jan. 20. The index finger on his shooting hand was taped Saturday and he missed a couple of easy shots in the first half, but Dayton still couldn't handle him. No other Musketeer scored until Romain Sato made a driving basket at 9:07 of the first half. Dayton built its lead to 28-13 as West's teammates went 0-for-8 from the field. West hit a 3-pointer from the top of the arc that sparked the comeback. He made 15 of Xavier's 28 baskets in all. "He's crafty and he takes what the defense gives him,'' Dayton forward Nate Green said. "He had the refs on his side, but he's got to be somewhat talented -- he dropped 45-50 on us.''
